JavaScript DOM

    - What is DOM?

        - DOM = Document Object Model
        - It represents the HTML page as a tree structure
        - JavaScript can use DOM to:
        - Select elements
        - Change content
        - Handle events

    In simple words:
    DOM allows JavaScript to control HTML & CSS

1.  Selecting Elements

    a. getElementById - usSelect elementing `id`

        Example:
        let heading = document.getElementById("title");

    b. querySelector - Select first matching element

        Example:
        let para = document.querySelector(".text"); // class
        let btn = document.querySelector("#btn"); // id
        let h1 = document.querySelector("h1"); // tag

    c. querySelectorAll - Select multiple elements (NodeList)

        Example:
        let items = document.querySelectorAll(".item");

2.  Changing Content

    a. innerText - Changes only text

        Example:
        heading.innerText = "Hello Aadit";

    b. innerHTML - Can add HTML inside element

        Example:
        heading.innerHTML = "<span>Hello</span>";

    Difference:

    `innerText` → text only
    `innerHTML` → supports HTML

3.  Changing Styles

    heading.style.color = "red";
    heading.style.backgroundColor = "yellow";

4.  JavaScript Events
    - What are Events?

      Events are actions performed by the user or browser
      JavaScript can respond to these actions

    Example:
    Click button
    Type in input
    Hover mouse
    - How to Add Event
      Syntax
      element.addEventListener("event", function)

    Common JavaScript Events
    1.  Click Event

        -Triggered when user clicks

            let btn = document.querySelector("#btn");

            btn.addEventListener("click", () => {
            console.log("Button Clicked");
            });

    2.  Double Click Event (dblclick)

        btn.addEventListener("dblclick", () => {
        console.log("Double Clicked");
        });

    3.  Mouse Over (mouseover)
        - When mouse enters element

          btn.addEventListener("mouseover", () => {
          console.log("Mouse Over");
          });

    4.  Mouse Out (mouseout)
        - When mouse leaves element

          btn.addEventListener("mouseout", () => {
          console.log("Mouse Out");
          });

    5.  Keydown Event
        - When key is pressed

          document.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => {
          console.log(e.key);
          });

    6.  Keyup Event
        - When key is released

          document.addEventListener("keyup", (e) => {
          console.log("Key Released");
          });

    7.  Input Event
        - When user types in input field

          let input = document.querySelector("#input");

          input.addEventListener("input", () => {
          console.log(input.value);
          });

    8.  Change Event
        - When input loses focus after change

          input.addEventListener("change", () => {
          console.log("Value Changed");
          });

    9.  Submit Event (Form)

        let form = document.querySelector("form");

        form.addEventListener("submit", (e) => {
        e.preventDefault(); // stop page reload
        console.log("Form Submitted");
        });
